<h1 id="soviet-joke-generator">Soviet Joke Generator</h1>
<p>Soviet Joke Generator is a Java program that randomly generates â€œIn Soviet Russiaâ€ jokes and compares the SHA-256 hash codes of two jokes to find the highest match. The jokes are constructed using random combinations of nouns and verbs, producing amusing sentences like â€œIn Soviet Russia, Bitcoin mine you.â€</p>

<h2 id="features">Features</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Generates random â€œIn Soviet Russiaâ€ jokes by combining a fixed phrase with random nouns and verbs.</li>
  <li>Uses SHA-256 hashing to compare jokes and find the highest matching characters in their hash codes.</li>
  <li>Writes over 1.7 million jokes to a file for analysis.</li>
  <li>Efficiently reads, writes, and processes large text files using <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">BufferedReader</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">BufferedWriter</code>.</li>
  <li>SHA-256 comparison implemented through Javaâ€™s <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">MessageDigest</code> class.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Java Development Kit (JDK) installed.</li>
  <li>Basic understanding of file handling in Java (<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">BufferedReader</code>, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">BufferedWriter</code>).</li>
  <li>Familiarity with SHA-256 hashing in Java.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="how-to-run">How to Run</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Clone the repository.</li>
  <li>Open the project in your preferred Java IDE.</li>
  <li>Run the program, which generates jokes, writes them to a file, and compares their SHA-256 hash codes.</li>
  <li>Observe the output of the two jokes with the highest match score.</li>
</ol>
